WEBVTT

00:15.056 --> 00:17.267
<i>♪ Oh, can you hear the sound now? ♪</i>

00:17.350 --> 00:19.185
<i>♪ Everybody catch my wave ♪</i>

00:19.269 --> 00:21.104
<i>♪ I can never leave this town now ♪</i>

00:21.187 --> 00:23.064
<i>♪ Everything goes my way ♪</i>

00:23.148 --> 00:24.899
<i>♪ Oh, can you hear the sound now? ♪</i>

00:24.983 --> 00:26.985
<i>♪ Everybody catch my wave ♪</i>

00:27.068 --> 00:28.820
<i>♪ I can never leave this town now ♪</i>

00:28.903 --> 00:30.822
<i>♪ Everything goes my way ♪</i>

00:30.905 --> 00:33.533
<i>December 20th
is the worst day of the year</i>

00:33.616 --> 00:36.494
<i>to travel through
John F. Kennedy International Airport.</i>

00:36.578 --> 00:40.415
<i>Over 193,000 passengers
arrive and depart that day...</i>

00:41.458 --> 00:43.626
<i>...causing, on average,
23-minute delays at check-in</i>

00:43.710 --> 00:46.921
<i>and a peak wait time
of 117 minutes at security.</i>

00:47.964 --> 00:50.842
<i>But of all the passengers inconvenienced
on this inconvenient day...</i>

00:50.925 --> 00:51.965
- Excuse me.
- Sorry.

00:52.010 --> 00:54.471
<i>...it is the story of only one that matters.</i>

00:54.554 --> 00:57.223
<i>Because today, that passenger is late.</i>

00:57.307 --> 00:58.516
Excuse me.

00:59.517 --> 01:01.269
- Whoa, whoa.
- Oh. Sorry. Sorry!

01:01.352 --> 01:03.872
<i>Hadley Sullivan is
about to miss her flight to London</i>

01:03.897 --> 01:04.730
<i>by four minutes.</i>

01:04.813 --> 01:06.274
Wait! Please, I'm here.

01:06.357 --> 01:09.402
Uh, sorry, miss. You're too late.

01:10.528 --> 01:13.281
<i>♪ Everything goes my way ♪</i>

01:15.825 --> 01:19.621
<i>There are 367 souls
aboard flight TA-5120.</i>

01:19.704 --> 01:22.665
<i>412 pieces of luggage, 344 personal items,</i>

01:22.749 --> 01:25.627
<i>4 emotional support animals,
and 62 neck pillows.</i>

01:26.252 --> 01:30.381
<i>Together, these passengers will travel
for 6 hours and 47 minutes,</i>

01:30.465 --> 01:32.258
<i>all without Hadley.</i>

01:32.342 --> 01:35.470
<i>Some might say it's bad luck
to miss one's flight by four minutes.</i>

01:35.553 --> 01:38.306
<i>Or you might prefer to think
that everything happens for a reason.</i>

01:38.389 --> 01:41.434
<i>But for Hadley, those four minutes
won't be unlucky at all.</i>

01:41.518 --> 01:44.813
Because very soon,
a girl and a boy will meet,

01:45.355 --> 01:47.482
and it will change everything.

01:50.235 --> 01:53.738
But just to be clear,
this isn't a story about love.

01:54.405 --> 01:56.616
This is a story about fate.

01:57.992 --> 01:58.993
Or statistics.

02:00.036 --> 02:01.955
Really just depends
on who you're talking to.

02:04.666 --> 02:06.668
<i>The girl
is Hadley Ella Sullivan.</i>

02:06.751 --> 02:08.794
<i>Twenty years old, 65 inches tall.</i>

02:08.877 --> 02:11.840
<i>She's late 21% of the time,
which is, coincidentally,</i>

02:11.923 --> 02:13.800
<i>the average battery life
of her cell phone.</i>

02:13.883 --> 02:15.552
<i>She's afraid of three things,</i>

02:15.635 --> 02:16.845
<i>including mayonnaise,</i>

02:17.554 --> 02:19.013
<i>small spaces,</i>

02:19.097 --> 02:20.348
<i>and dentists.</i>

02:20.890 --> 02:23.685
<i>There was one thing, however,
she never thought to be afraid of.</i>

02:23.768 --> 02:24.811
It's just for a term.

02:24.894 --> 02:28.815
Dad, you're literally gonna be teaching
poetry in the country Shakespeare's from.

02:28.898 --> 02:31.901
- How are you not freaking out right now?
- Oh, I'm freakin' out.

02:31.985 --> 02:34.362
This is awesome.
I've always wanted to study abroad...

02:34.445 --> 02:38.491
Actually, honey,
you and I are staying here.

02:39.117 --> 02:40.285
Why?

02:40.869 --> 02:44.122
<i>She wasn't ready to admit it,
but on her list of fears,</i>

02:44.205 --> 02:47.667
<i>divorce suddenly ranked
much higher than mayonnaise.</i>

02:48.710 --> 02:51.880
The best thing we can do
is get you on the next flight.

02:51.963 --> 02:54.507
There are two seats left,
both in business.

02:54.591 --> 02:56.926
- When does that leave?
- Hour and a half.

02:57.010 --> 02:59.095
Arrives in London at 9:55 a.m.

02:59.179 --> 03:02.056
- My dad's wedding's at noon.
- Do you need to think about it?

03:03.391 --> 03:05.768
You know, can you give me one second?
I'll just be...

03:05.852 --> 03:07.103
Sorry, just one second.

03:07.770 --> 03:09.564
Just, uh...

03:15.486 --> 03:17.280
Hey, sweetie. What's up?

03:17.363 --> 03:19.699
- Hey, I, uh, missed my flight.
- What?

03:19.782 --> 03:22.493
Yeah, I can get on the next one,
but there's only business.

03:22.577 --> 03:23.737
It doesn't get in till 10:00.

03:23.786 --> 03:25.121
Tomorrow?

03:25.705 --> 03:28.458
- No, tonight. I'll be traveling by comet.
<i>- Hadley.</i>

03:28.541 --> 03:29.584
<i>Sorry.</i>

03:29.667 --> 03:33.087
All right, well, buy the ticket,
and... and I'll reimburse you.

03:33.171 --> 03:35.882
- Uh, no, I can pay for it.
- Don't be ridiculous.

03:35.965 --> 03:38.301
- You can't afford that.
<i>- Okay. Thank you.</i>

03:38.885 --> 03:40.220
I really have to go.

03:40.303 --> 03:41.346
<i>All right.</i>

03:41.429 --> 03:43.723
Well, text me right when you land, okay?

03:43.806 --> 03:44.891
Yeah, okay.

03:44.974 --> 03:46.601
- Bye.
<i>- Bye.</i>

03:49.395 --> 03:50.271
Okay, yeah.

03:50.355 --> 03:52.523
One business-class ticket
to London, please.

03:54.567 --> 03:55.944
Thank you. Thanks.

03:56.611 --> 03:57.445
Sorry.

03:58.613 --> 04:00.698
<i>If you see any unattended luggage</i>

04:00.782 --> 04:04.786
<i>or anything suspicious,
contact the TSA immediately.</i>

04:04.869 --> 04:07.455
<i>If you see something, say something.</i>

04:08.164 --> 04:09.874
Oh. It's dead.

04:09.958 --> 04:11.125
So that's why it's open.

04:12.710 --> 04:13.795
Course it is.

04:14.879 --> 04:16.422
- What?
- Um...

04:16.505 --> 04:18.382
Never mind. Nothing. Thank you.

04:18.466 --> 04:23.012
<i>...boarding announcement for flight AI-3670...</i>

04:23.096 --> 04:24.472
You can borrow mine if you want.

04:30.687 --> 04:33.314
<i>This,
as you may have guessed, is the boy.</i>

04:33.398 --> 04:37.235
<i>Oliver Martin Jones,
22 years old, 1.8 meters tall.</i>

04:37.318 --> 04:39.404
<i>He is on time 94% of the time,</i>

04:39.487 --> 04:41.367
<i>which is coincidentally
the average battery life</i>

04:41.406 --> 04:42.573
<i>on</i> his <i>mobile phone.</i>

04:43.283 --> 04:45.743
<i>He too has always
been afraid of three things,</i>

04:45.827 --> 04:47.704
<i>germs, the dark...</i>

04:48.705 --> 04:49.705
<i>...and surprises.</i>

04:51.874 --> 04:53.042
Here is the scroll...

04:53.126 --> 04:54.002
The scroll?

04:54.085 --> 05:00.133
...on which is writ
every man's name that is thought fit

05:00.216 --> 05:01.216
in all...

05:04.304 --> 05:06.064
At the moment,
it's still localized.

05:06.097 --> 05:08.534
With the right course of treatment,
her chances are very good.

05:08.558 --> 05:10.643
These things aren't always predictable.

05:10.727 --> 05:15.023
<i>It was then that Oliver decided
he'd never be surprised like that again.</i>

05:15.106 --> 05:17.734
Everything in our lives
is now measured by big data.

05:17.817 --> 05:21.112
Our social connections,
our buying habits, even our daily steps.

05:21.195 --> 05:23.364
That means that eventually, one day,

05:23.448 --> 05:25.325
everything in our lives
will be predictable.

05:25.408 --> 05:28.369
I think there's always some things
that will catch us by surprise.

05:29.162 --> 05:30.997
Not if we have enough data.

05:32.290 --> 05:33.970
<i>When you're afraid
of surprises,</i>

05:34.000 --> 05:36.294
<i>it can seem better
to leave nothing to chance.</i>

05:37.462 --> 05:38.463
Borrow mine, if you want.

05:38.546 --> 05:41.424
<i>That is,
until you meet an American girl</i>

05:41.507 --> 05:42.592
<i>with a dead phone battery.</i>

05:44.093 --> 05:47.305
Sorry, I don't, uh,
share electronics till the third date.

05:49.599 --> 05:51.851
Okay. No, I...
I suppose it <i>is</i> quite intimate.

05:54.103 --> 05:55.688
Mm-hmm.

05:57.440 --> 05:58.983
Yeah, I'm done, if you wanna use it.

05:59.067 --> 06:01.235
Oh, uh... thanks. I...

06:02.111 --> 06:03.029
Battery keeps dying.

06:03.112 --> 06:05.031
It probably just needs a service.

06:05.114 --> 06:07.784
Phone batteries, they have
a finite number of charging cycles.

06:07.867 --> 06:09.869
You, like, a tech bro, or...

06:09.952 --> 06:11.412
A maths geek.

06:11.913 --> 06:13.748
I'm studying statistics at Yale.

06:14.707 --> 06:15.707
Wow.

06:17.543 --> 06:18.836
Subtle status drop there.

06:20.296 --> 06:23.049
British, you know? Can't help myself.

06:26.302 --> 06:27.428
I'm Oliver, by the way.

06:28.721 --> 06:29.721
As in Twist?

06:30.431 --> 06:32.517
And they say Americans are uncultured.

06:32.600 --> 06:36.187
Oh. We definitely are.
I'm just a Dickens fan.

06:36.938 --> 06:37.772
I'm Hadley.

06:37.855 --> 06:39.273
Well, it's nice to meet you.

06:40.191 --> 06:41.067
Nice to meet you.

06:43.152 --> 06:45.279
What are you studying, Dickens fan Hadley?

06:46.030 --> 06:49.450
- English lit?
- I'm...  ...undecided.

06:49.534 --> 06:51.494
It's not like I woke up one morning
and was like,

06:51.577 --> 06:53.704
"Oh, I'm gonna be
a tax law attorney."

06:53.788 --> 06:55.665
Does that happen to anyone?

06:55.748 --> 06:57.625
Tax attorneys, probably.

07:00.628 --> 07:02.046
Where are you headed?

07:02.964 --> 07:04.298
Uh, London. You?

07:05.049 --> 07:06.676
Same. Yeah, I'm actually, uh...

07:06.759 --> 07:09.303
...I'm supposed to be
in the air currently.

07:09.387 --> 07:11.639
- But I missed my flight by four minutes.
- Ooh.

07:12.974 --> 07:14.600
I... I'd say it was fate,

07:14.684 --> 07:16.936
but you probably <i>chose</i>
to be four minutes late.

07:17.437 --> 07:19.105
Hmm.

07:23.693 --> 07:25.403
I was gonna go get some food.

07:25.486 --> 07:26.654
Do you wanna come with?

07:27.321 --> 07:30.616
Is that, like,
a... third date thing for you?

07:32.493 --> 07:34.829
No, food would be great.

07:35.538 --> 07:38.958
<i>Ordinarily, Hadley's
perpetual tardiness and uncharged phone</i>

07:39.041 --> 07:40.334
<i>led her to get into trouble.</i>

07:40.835 --> 07:43.379
<i>Today, it led her to Oliver.</i>

07:43.463 --> 07:45.590
Are you heading home
for the holidays?

07:45.673 --> 07:47.550
I assume that London is your home.

07:48.259 --> 07:49.899
Yeah. To be honest, I'd rather stay here.

07:49.969 --> 07:51.637
Don't wanna get behind on my research.

07:51.721 --> 07:53.014
What are you researching?

07:53.097 --> 07:55.391
The percentage of Americans
who miss their flights.

07:55.892 --> 07:57.351
Hmm.

07:57.435 --> 07:58.978
Hilarious. Very funny.

07:59.061 --> 08:01.105
Oh. Ew.

08:01.189 --> 08:03.149
- That's nasty.
- Ah.

08:03.232 --> 08:05.568
I've got a Lysol wipe for you.

08:05.651 --> 08:07.862
For your dirty, dying phone.

08:08.571 --> 08:10.406
Thank you.

08:10.490 --> 08:12.783
I've always, uh, hated airports.

08:12.867 --> 08:13.701
Really?

08:13.784 --> 08:14.994
I love 'em.

08:15.077 --> 08:16.078
Why?

08:16.162 --> 08:18.831
I like how you're neither here
nor there, you're just

08:20.249 --> 08:21.334
in no-man's-land.

08:21.417 --> 08:22.877
No, it sounds lovely.

08:22.960 --> 08:23.961
Just like purgatory.

08:27.632 --> 08:28.632
Not a carbs guy?

08:29.050 --> 08:30.968
No, I just... I just hate mayonnaise.

08:32.053 --> 08:33.053
- Really?
- Yeah.

08:33.095 --> 08:35.722
- It's a disgusting condiment...
- I hate it too, actually.

08:35.806 --> 08:37.140
Um, it's, uh,

08:37.850 --> 08:39.644
number two of my top three fears.

08:39.727 --> 08:42.270
- What are the others?
- Dentists and small spaces.

08:43.022 --> 08:45.022
- You've thought about this.
- Not really.

08:45.066 --> 08:46.901
Like, if I were to ask
what you're afraid of,

08:46.984 --> 08:48.736
you wouldn't have to think.
You would know.

08:48.819 --> 08:50.446
Well, how do you know I'm not fearless?

08:50.530 --> 08:53.491
'Cause you are eating deli meat
with a fork and knife.

08:58.579 --> 08:59.789
Sorry, I gotta take this.

08:59.872 --> 09:00.915
Oh yeah. Go for it.

09:03.042 --> 09:05.002
<i>You did say 11:00
you were getting in?</i>

09:05.086 --> 09:07.213
No, it's 10:00. I emailed you.

09:07.296 --> 09:08.464
You did?

09:08.548 --> 09:10.716
I blame the gym's Wi-Fi. It's a bit dodgy.

09:10.800 --> 09:13.261
<i>You've got one job tomorrow.
Pick me up at 10:00.</i>

09:13.344 --> 09:14.424
Don't worry. I'll be there.

09:14.470 --> 09:18.266
And by the way, I've got a little surprise
planned for you, so... be ready for that.

09:18.349 --> 09:20.142
What? No, I don't like surprises.

09:20.226 --> 09:21.978
It's a good one. You can't be annoyed.

09:22.061 --> 09:24.063
I've warned you,
so you can't be as pissed.

09:24.146 --> 09:25.226
What kind of logic is that?

09:25.815 --> 09:26.732
<i>Luther, no.</i>

09:26.816 --> 09:29.652
<i>I don't want a surprise.
You think they're all good. None are good.</i>

09:29.735 --> 09:32.071
No, sorry, Wi-Fi's breaking up.
No, I can't hear you.

09:32.154 --> 09:33.906
Luth. Luther!

09:42.957 --> 09:44.917
- Sorry about that.
- Okay.

09:45.459 --> 09:48.754
So if claustrophobia
is one of your biggest fears,

09:48.838 --> 09:51.299
then why are you about
to embark on a seven-hour flight?

09:51.382 --> 09:52.902
That <i>is</i> a very good question.

09:52.967 --> 09:53.967
A wedding.

09:55.136 --> 09:56.262
Same as you?

09:57.096 --> 09:58.139
Right.

09:58.931 --> 10:01.017
That is actually my loungewear.

10:01.100 --> 10:03.185
So I like to relax
in a finely pressed suit.

10:03.269 --> 10:04.353
Hey, I get it.

10:04.854 --> 10:06.105
Wrinkles are stressful.

10:06.188 --> 10:08.608
<i>...to London Heathrow...</i>

10:08.691 --> 10:10.151
Did he just call our flight?

10:10.735 --> 10:12.528
- Already?
- Um, uh...

10:12.612 --> 10:15.698
Shoot, I can't miss another one. So...

10:15.781 --> 10:17.821
Oh. This way.

10:17.867 --> 10:19.970
- Backpack. Thank you!
- I'll get it.

10:19.994 --> 10:21.787
That's very kind.

10:21.871 --> 10:23.706
<i>♪ I can never leave this town now ♪</i>

10:23.789 --> 10:25.625
<i>♪ Everything goes my way ♪</i>

10:25.708 --> 10:27.501
<i>♪ Oh, can you hear the sound now? ♪</i>

10:27.585 --> 10:29.420
<i>♪ Everybody catch my wave ♪</i>

10:29.503 --> 10:31.213
<i>♪ I can never leave this town now ♪</i>

10:31.297 --> 10:32.465
<i>♪ Everything goes my way ♪</i>

10:32.548 --> 10:33.799
<i>♪ Everything goes my way... ♪</i>

10:39.305 --> 10:41.307
<i>- ♪ Everything goes my way... ♪</i>
- Wait! Wait!

10:41.390 --> 10:43.851
Oh.

10:44.560 --> 10:46.646
Great. We're here. We made it. Okay.

10:46.729 --> 10:48.105
<i>♪ Everything goes my way ♪</i>

10:48.189 --> 10:49.207
- Thank you.
- Mm.

10:49.231 --> 10:50.733
<i>♪ Good health every day ♪</i>

10:50.816 --> 10:52.736
<i>♪ Crossin' our heart
That we're here to stay... ♪</i>

10:53.152 --> 10:54.612
- Thank you.
- Phew.

10:56.656 --> 10:59.200
<i>- ♪ Now come, come for me ♪</i>
- You're really fast.

10:59.283 --> 11:01.786
<i>♪ I'll drop you a line
You say we're movin' slow ♪</i>

11:01.869 --> 11:03.913
<i>♪ I say we're doin' all right ♪</i>

11:03.996 --> 11:06.207
<i>♪ Come, come for me ♪</i>

11:06.290 --> 11:07.917
<i>♪ I'll drop you a line ♪</i>

11:08.000 --> 11:09.377
<i>♪ You say we're movin' slow ♪</i>

11:09.460 --> 11:11.962
<i>♪ I say we're doin' all right ♪</i>

11:12.046 --> 11:13.172
Well, this is me.

11:13.756 --> 11:14.757
Oh!

11:14.840 --> 11:15.840
Very nice.

11:16.634 --> 11:17.510
I'm further back, so...

11:17.593 --> 11:19.845
Hello, madam.
May I help you find your seat?

11:19.929 --> 11:21.972
- I'm right here. I'm good, thanks.
- Okay.

11:22.056 --> 11:23.349
- Excuse me.
- Sure.

11:23.432 --> 11:24.433
Thank you.

11:24.517 --> 11:26.811
- Let me get that for you.
- Oh. Thank you.

11:29.188 --> 11:30.189
Sorry.

11:31.899 --> 11:34.235
Back to the gym.

11:34.318 --> 11:35.569
Um, sorry. One sec.

11:35.653 --> 11:38.447
Um, it's, uh, lovely to meet you, Hadley.

11:38.531 --> 11:39.531
Yeah.

11:39.990 --> 11:41.534
- Good luck.
- You too.

11:44.704 --> 11:45.871
"Good luck"?

11:45.955 --> 11:47.289
What a knob.

12:08.519 --> 12:09.854
- Evening.
- All right, mate.

12:31.459 --> 12:32.501
Uh, excuse me, miss.

12:34.170 --> 12:36.464
- Yes, sir?
- I think my seat belt is broken.

12:36.547 --> 12:38.007
Oh. May I?

12:38.632 --> 12:39.467
Oh. Nope.

12:39.550 --> 12:40.550
Stay.

12:43.596 --> 12:45.347
You're right. Oh dear.

12:45.431 --> 12:46.432
What?

12:46.515 --> 12:48.392
You can't fly without a working seat belt.

12:48.476 --> 12:49.643
I have to be on this flight.

12:49.727 --> 12:52.414
- It's a safety issue.
- Is there somewhere else I can sit?

12:52.438 --> 12:54.118
I'll strap myself into cargo if I have to.

12:54.774 --> 12:56.734
Sit tight, lovely.
I'll see if we can move you.

12:56.817 --> 12:57.817
Thank you.

12:58.736 --> 13:01.238
Mom, hi. I missed my flight.

13:01.322 --> 13:03.365
But I got on the next one,
so everything's fine.

13:03.449 --> 13:06.118
Um, I'll call you when I land.
Okay? I love you. Bye.

13:07.328 --> 13:09.580
- Thank you for this.
- It's nothing.

13:09.663 --> 13:12.958
Look, technically we're not supposed
to move from economy to business,

13:13.042 --> 13:14.042
but, um,

13:14.835 --> 13:16.504
today just happens to be your lucky day.

13:18.255 --> 13:19.089
Hadley.

13:19.173 --> 13:20.173
Oliver.

13:21.550 --> 13:23.552
- What are you...
- My seat belt's broken.

13:23.636 --> 13:25.476
- They have to move me.
- I'm sorry.

13:26.055 --> 13:27.223
Do you two know each other?

13:27.306 --> 13:29.016
- Yeah...
- Sort of, um...

13:30.267 --> 13:32.394
Then I guess
this really <i>is</i> your lucky day.

13:34.522 --> 13:35.981
Well, this is unexpected.

13:36.065 --> 13:39.527
I would've thought you'd seen it coming,
Mr. Predictive Analytics.

13:40.861 --> 13:42.988
All right, okay. Very good.

13:43.072 --> 13:44.990
Well done.

13:45.074 --> 13:46.826
- Hmm.
- Do you always get pj's?

13:46.909 --> 13:49.495
I've actually
never flown business either.

13:51.539 --> 13:53.123
Do you mind if I...

13:53.624 --> 13:54.984
- Oh, thank you.
- Wipe you down...

13:55.042 --> 13:57.169
Uh, not, uh, like that.

13:57.253 --> 13:59.755
29% of airplanes
are not cleaned thoroughly.

14:01.507 --> 14:02.675
I... I made that one up.

14:10.349 --> 14:12.434
Over the next 6 hours and 47 minutes,

14:12.518 --> 14:15.271
Hadley Sullivan
and Oliver Jones will fall in love.

14:19.400 --> 14:21.485
But then, 18 minutes after they land,

14:21.569 --> 14:24.697
they'll be separated in a crowd
and never see each other again.

14:25.823 --> 14:30.411
Well, that's unless they get each other's
name or number or email,

14:30.494 --> 14:32.663
Instagram, LinkedIn, Twitter, Facebook.

14:33.706 --> 14:35.708
There's loads of options, really.

14:37.251 --> 14:39.044
Great.

14:43.883 --> 14:46.319
{\an8}<i>In case of an emergency landing in water,</i>

14:46.343 --> 14:48.762
<i>your life jacket is located
under your seat</i>

14:48.846 --> 14:50.514
<i>and will inflate automatically.</i>

14:50.598 --> 14:53.225
<i>It has a whistle
for you to use for attention</i>

14:53.309 --> 14:55.477
<i>and a light
so you can be seen in the dark...</i>

14:56.270 --> 14:57.270
What?

14:57.730 --> 14:59.370
I've never seen anyone read those before.

14:59.398 --> 15:01.609
Well, then you're very lucky
to be sitting next to me.

15:01.692 --> 15:02.735
Oh. You mean in general?

15:03.611 --> 15:05.029
And in case of an emergency.

15:05.112 --> 15:07.406
Right, 'cause if we crash-land
into the pond,

15:07.489 --> 15:10.034
then all five-foot-nothing of you

15:10.117 --> 15:12.328
is gonna pick me up
and carry me out of there.

15:12.411 --> 15:14.538
You know the chances
of this plane crashing are, like,

15:14.622 --> 15:16.165
one in five and a half million.

15:16.665 --> 15:18.465
You're more likely to die
on your ride home...

15:18.542 --> 15:20.127
Can we not talk about dying right now?

15:21.712 --> 15:23.005
- Sorry.
- It's okay.

15:25.090 --> 15:27.384
<i>Cabin crew, prepare for takeoff.</i>

15:57.414 --> 15:58.414
You okay?

15:59.208 --> 16:00.250
Mm-hmm.

16:03.504 --> 16:06.256
Um, what's your... favorite color?

16:07.758 --> 16:08.758
Food?

16:09.093 --> 16:10.386
Animal?

16:11.595 --> 16:13.389
Seriously?

16:13.472 --> 16:14.472
Come on.

16:16.892 --> 16:18.852
Yellow, Mexican, dogs. You?

16:19.603 --> 16:21.647
Blue, curry, and birds.

16:21.730 --> 16:23.107
Birds.

16:23.190 --> 16:24.191
Ew.

16:24.274 --> 16:26.652
What do you mean, "Ew"?
They're the symbol of freedom.

16:26.735 --> 16:27.861
They shit everywhere.

16:27.945 --> 16:29.571
So do dogs.

16:29.655 --> 16:30.823
Dogs aren't creepy.

16:31.448 --> 16:33.575
Okay. What's your favorite number?

16:33.659 --> 16:35.661
Um... two.

16:35.744 --> 16:36.578
You?

16:36.662 --> 16:37.662
<i>i.</i>

16:39.581 --> 16:40.916
It's the imaginary unit.

16:41.000 --> 16:43.168
It's the square root of negative one.

16:44.253 --> 16:46.338
- Wow. You're such a nerd.
- I know.

16:46.922 --> 16:48.924
Maybe. But I think it's working.

16:50.300 --> 16:51.552
What, you being charming?

16:52.678 --> 16:54.263
No. Me distracting you.

16:57.808 --> 17:00.019
It's good to know
that you think I'm charming, though.

17:04.857 --> 17:07.502
<i>The captain
has switched off the seat belt light,</i>

17:07.526 --> 17:09.778
<i>so please feel free
to move around the cabin.</i>

17:09.862 --> 17:10.945
<i>In a few moments,</i>

17:11.030 --> 17:12.869
<i>the flight attendants
will be passing around...</i>

17:12.906 --> 17:13.906
Thank you for that.

17:14.366 --> 17:15.367
No worries.

17:16.743 --> 17:17.994
I'll get that for you.

17:18.078 --> 17:20.372
- Oh, thank you, young man.
- That's okay.

17:22.082 --> 17:24.376
- You got a good one there.
- Thanks.

17:24.460 --> 17:25.752
How'd you two meet?

17:25.836 --> 17:29.214
- Actually, we...
- It was at an airport, believe it or not.

17:29.298 --> 17:30.424
Really?

17:30.507 --> 17:32.718
Yeah. See, um, her phone was dead,

17:32.801 --> 17:35.596
so I gallantly offered her my charger.

17:36.263 --> 17:37.598
We started chatting.

17:37.681 --> 17:38.849
One thing led to another...

17:38.932 --> 17:41.310
And he's been charging
my batteries ever since.

17:41.393 --> 17:42.728
Oh, good for you two.

17:44.605 --> 17:46.523
Anyway, have a nice flight.

17:46.607 --> 17:47.608
You too.

17:48.275 --> 17:50.736
So, tell me more about this wedding.

17:51.862 --> 17:53.489
Oh, yeah, uh...

17:54.031 --> 17:55.031
Yeah, um...

17:55.741 --> 17:59.536
It's my dad's second marriage

17:59.620 --> 18:01.205
to a woman I've never met before.

18:01.288 --> 18:02.539
So...

18:03.582 --> 18:05.542
- So you're going to your dad's wedding.
- Yep.

18:06.043 --> 18:07.753
And you've never met his fiancée.

18:07.836 --> 18:09.171
- Nope.
- How does that work?

18:11.381 --> 18:12.382
Well...

18:12.466 --> 18:18.305
Um, it starts when he gets
a job teaching poetry at Oxford.

18:18.388 --> 18:21.100
Then after promising
that that will only last for a semester,

18:21.183 --> 18:24.436
he files for divorce from your mom

18:24.520 --> 18:27.523
and falls in love
with a woman named Charlotte

18:27.606 --> 18:30.109
and proceeds to ask her to marry him.

18:30.192 --> 18:33.570
And then he makes you,
who he hasn't seen for over a year,

18:33.654 --> 18:36.490
fly across the ocean in a tin can

18:36.573 --> 18:39.868
so you can stand next to him
wearing a dress the color of a bruise.

18:39.952 --> 18:41.286
That's awful.

18:41.370 --> 18:43.539
Yeah.

18:43.622 --> 18:48.168
If it's, uh, any consolation,
50% of marriages do end in divorce.

18:48.877 --> 18:50.129
That means 50% don't.

18:50.212 --> 18:54.591
Yeah, but I mean, the chances
of this happening were incredibly high.

18:54.675 --> 18:56.395
Is that supposed
to make me feel any better?

18:56.468 --> 18:57.886
- Doesn't it?
- No.

18:57.970 --> 18:59.471
I think it just sucks.

19:00.305 --> 19:01.974
You know, the worst part is that

19:02.975 --> 19:04.643
he's gonna get up tomorrow,

19:04.726 --> 19:06.406
and he's gonna make
the exact same promises

19:06.478 --> 19:07.479
that he just broke.

19:08.272 --> 19:10.023
I get that people can fall in love again.

19:10.107 --> 19:11.347
I just feel like, if it's real,

19:11.400 --> 19:13.152
why do you have to try
so hard to prove it?

19:13.235 --> 19:18.615
Why do you have to throw this big,
grand party to rub it in everyone's face?

19:19.449 --> 19:22.244
I think that real love isn't about that.

19:23.287 --> 19:25.414
Real love is about finding someone

19:26.206 --> 19:28.625
that will hold your hand
when life gets rough.

19:29.501 --> 19:30.501
And that's it?

19:31.420 --> 19:36.008
No wedding, no marriage, just...
someone to hold your hand through life?

19:37.759 --> 19:38.759
Yeah, pretty much.

19:42.681 --> 19:46.018
I like that...
weddings are a promise, I guess.

19:48.228 --> 19:50.189
Not everyone keeps their promises.

19:52.858 --> 19:54.067
Anyways,

19:55.027 --> 19:56.820
that's my wedding.

19:56.904 --> 19:57.904
What's yours?

19:57.946 --> 20:01.283
Please say something dramatic,
like your stepmom's marrying your uncle

20:01.366 --> 20:02.618
or something like that.

20:02.701 --> 20:05.037
- Um...
- So what'll it be?

20:05.120 --> 20:09.041
Some delicious chicken and vegetables,
or some... very dry fish?

20:09.625 --> 20:10.709
- Chicken.
- Mm.

20:10.792 --> 20:12.127
- Right.
- Um...

20:12.211 --> 20:14.379
I'm gonna go for the fish...

20:16.173 --> 20:17.007
Chicken.

20:17.090 --> 20:18.425
Excellent choice, madam.

20:19.968 --> 20:21.929
- Wow, our second dinner date.
- Hmm.

20:22.012 --> 20:23.805
Things are moving fast.

20:33.065 --> 20:34.149
For you.

20:52.209 --> 20:54.086
All right?

20:54.169 --> 20:55.420
Yeah. Sorry, I...

20:56.296 --> 20:57.339
Oh my God.

20:58.423 --> 21:00.300
- I mean...
- Sexy, I know.

21:00.968 --> 21:02.636
- Perfect fit.
- I thought so.

21:02.719 --> 21:04.012
Look cute.

21:05.681 --> 21:07.182
Oh, you weren't lying about Dickens.

21:07.266 --> 21:08.267
Oh, um...

21:08.892 --> 21:11.228
...I actually haven't read this one.

21:11.311 --> 21:13.081
- Hmm. Looks like someone has.
- Yeah.

21:13.105 --> 21:17.150
Um, it was my dad's.
He gave it to me after the divorce.

21:17.234 --> 21:19.278
It was a thing that we would do.

21:19.361 --> 21:22.281
He would give me books he loved,
and then I would love them too.

21:24.866 --> 21:26.326
It's one of his best ones.

21:26.410 --> 21:28.328
I've read it... at least a dozen times.

21:28.829 --> 21:31.915
You know, I don't get to recommend books
as often to you now.

21:32.499 --> 21:35.752
But certain ones are too important
to get lost in all this.

21:37.796 --> 21:38.796
Thanks.

21:39.214 --> 21:41.008
So, should we hit the slopes?

21:44.011 --> 21:46.888
Yeah. Um, just gotta pee first.

21:57.065 --> 21:59.860
"'Is it better
to have had a good thing and lost it,

22:00.360 --> 22:01.737
or never to have had it?'"

22:07.784 --> 22:09.369
<i>That's why I'm giving it back.</i>

22:09.911 --> 22:11.621
Without having read it.

22:11.705 --> 22:12.873
Without having read it.

22:13.707 --> 22:15.417
Right.

22:18.503 --> 22:21.840
Do you wanna join me
at the cinema?

22:21.923 --> 22:25.177
Make our first date dinner
and a nice, cheesy rom-com?

22:26.595 --> 22:28.096
I'm down for a cheesy rom-com.

22:29.473 --> 22:31.350
As long as there's a happy ending.

22:32.434 --> 22:33.434
You know what I meant.

22:34.061 --> 22:35.062
Okay.

22:35.145 --> 22:36.646
- I meant like...
- No. No, it's fine.

22:36.730 --> 22:38.374
- In the movie with the characters...
- Hey.

22:38.398 --> 22:40.442
I like happy endings.

23:13.225 --> 23:14.643
<i>Oh, let us come to the gate.</i>

23:14.726 --> 23:16.520
- Let us come with you.
- Mom, I'm 21.

23:16.603 --> 23:17.896
- Just come to the...
- No!

23:17.979 --> 23:19.147
Okay, well, work hard,

23:19.231 --> 23:21.358
but... don't forget to play.

23:21.441 --> 23:22.275
I will.

23:22.359 --> 23:24.712
- And make sure you eat... properly.
- Same to you.

23:24.736 --> 23:26.488
I'm so proud of you.

23:27.197 --> 23:28.407
Okay. Go.

23:28.490 --> 23:29.490
Go on then.

23:30.200 --> 23:31.200
Live your life.

23:31.743 --> 23:33.370
Have a grand adventure!

23:33.870 --> 23:35.372
Farewell!

23:35.455 --> 23:36.498
Toodle-oo.

23:36.581 --> 23:38.083
Bye!

23:56.226 --> 23:57.602
Are you preparing a speech?

23:59.062 --> 24:00.062
Yeah.

24:00.897 --> 24:01.940
Best man?

24:03.233 --> 24:05.444
That's what they tell me.

24:06.403 --> 24:07.612
You get some rest?

24:07.696 --> 24:08.696
Little bit.

24:11.158 --> 24:14.661
I was thinking about it, and...
I don't think you should give it back.

24:15.287 --> 24:16.287
The book.

24:16.705 --> 24:17.705
Why not?

24:18.832 --> 24:21.877
Well, historically,
you and your dad were very close,

24:21.960 --> 24:25.839
which means the odds are
you will eventually forgive him.

24:27.048 --> 24:28.925
So you might as well just do it now.

24:29.843 --> 24:31.678
You and the math thing.

24:31.761 --> 24:33.180
Mm.

24:33.847 --> 24:35.974
Yeah, drives my brother nuts too.

24:36.057 --> 24:37.392
You have siblings?

24:37.476 --> 24:39.144
Uh, yeah, one.

24:39.227 --> 24:41.313
He's two years younger. Luther.

24:41.396 --> 24:43.190
Does he live in London?

24:43.273 --> 24:44.774
Yeah, with our mum and dad.

24:44.858 --> 24:46.276
Well, until a few months ago

24:46.359 --> 24:49.696
when he decided to buy
a garish green Sprinter van.

24:49.779 --> 24:51.698
Hmm. Those are cool.

24:51.781 --> 24:52.781
Mm.

24:53.617 --> 24:55.202
That's what he tells me.

24:55.285 --> 24:57.829
Are you guys close, historically?

25:01.041 --> 25:03.543
- You ask a lot of questions, don't you?
- Are you?

25:05.921 --> 25:07.506
Our mum got sick when we were kids.

25:08.256 --> 25:10.634
So, yeah. But we're both very different.

25:11.927 --> 25:13.803
It's fine, though. I'm used to it now.

25:15.972 --> 25:17.265
She okay now, your mom?

25:18.183 --> 25:20.936
Uh, she was in remission
for 14 years, but it came back.

25:23.146 --> 25:24.146
I'm sorry.

25:25.315 --> 25:26.775
Oh no...

25:36.576 --> 25:38.703
You're sort of dangerous.
Do you know that?

25:39.663 --> 25:40.663
Me?

25:44.376 --> 25:45.376
Yeah.

25:46.211 --> 25:47.629
I'm way too honest with you.

25:53.885 --> 25:58.557
Anyway, I should nip to the loo
and then get some sleep, I think.

25:59.724 --> 26:00.724
Yeah, same.

26:01.518 --> 26:03.478
<i>♪ I've been in love ♪</i>

26:03.562 --> 26:06.398
<i>♪ And lost my senses ♪</i>

26:07.190 --> 26:09.359
<i>♪ Spinnin' through the town ♪</i>

26:12.153 --> 26:16.157
<i>♪ Sooner or later, the fever ends ♪</i>

26:16.241 --> 26:20.203
<i>♪ And I wind up feeling down ♪</i>

26:22.831 --> 26:24.541
<i>- ♪ I need a man ♪</i>
- Excuse me.

26:24.624 --> 26:26.835
<i>- ♪ Who'll take a chance ♪</i>
- Oh.

26:26.918 --> 26:32.591
<i>♪ On a love
That burns hot enough to last ♪</i>

26:33.592 --> 26:35.885
<i>♪ When the night falls ♪</i>

26:36.720 --> 26:39.556
<i>♪ My lonely heart calls ♪</i>

26:44.603 --> 26:48.607
